title: Collapsible spool holder with bearings (Anycubic i3 Mega)

description.text:
There are no more things than spool holders. And yet here's another one for the Anycubic I3 Mega. It might be a little bit over-engineered. Basically if one remixes the plate part this can be used on other machines, too.

I wanted the spool to be as much free running as possible. As I have another machine, which has pretty good designed holders, I choose to adapt that design. Additionally I tried to make the holder collapsible. In collaped state the holder will not make the printer wider.

You will need one of each part: plate, mount_round, mount_angular and mount_dome. The dome will fit into mount_angular. The round and angular mount will fit together. For actually holding a spool two LARGE_SPOOL_MOUNT.stl are needed.

There are additional parts required:

  • 2x M8 x 70mm screw
  • 4x 8mm (unsealed) bearing (type 608)
  • 6x M8 locking nut
  • 2x 8mm steel ball
  • 2x 25mm x 6mm spring
  • 2x M3 x 10mm bolt
  • 8x M3 x 25 bolt
  • 8x M3 nut

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.15-0.2

Infill:

20%-25%

Notes:

Mount parts should be rotated by 90° before slicing. Use touch bed supports for them. This reduces support material.

I suggest to leave the spool mount parts as is and use supports everywhere. Then some of the support material at the inside of the mounts even can stay there.

Plate and dome can be printed as they are in the file. Use touch bed support for plate too.

Plate
  • put one M8 bolt into the plate part from the back
  • put one bearing onto the bolt
  • screw one of the locking nuts onto the bolt until it fixes the bearing
  • screw a second nut onto the bolt
  • leave exactly a gap of 14.25mm between the nuts (use calipers)
  • place a second bearing on the bolt
  • screw a third nut onto the bolt and fix the second bearing
  • check: there should be a gap of 30mm between the bearings
Mount

The mount consists of th parts mount_round, mount_angular and mount_dome.

for each mount half:

  • place a 8mm steel ball in the tube
  • slide in a spring
  • tension the spring using a fine screw driver, allen key or equal
  • screw in a M3 x 10mm bolt to keep the spring in place
  • (I know this is tricky)

The ball should be visible at the opening and there should be a pretty good tension when pushing the ball in.

  • place the second M8 bolt into the angular half
  • place the mount_dome onto the bolt
  • proceed like you did with the plate part
  • (bearings, nuts, measurement)
  • place the two halfes on the bolt of the plate part. They should match the bearings. Try to rest the steel balls in the sinks.
  • screw them together using M3 x 25mm bolts and M3 nuts. (You might prepare the nuts before if they fit tightly.)

The mount should rest in one of the two positions and be movable to the other position with some force.

Spool holder

As you might guess now, place two halfes of LARGE_SPOOL_MOUNT on the previously finished mount and screw them together with M3 x 25mm bolts and M3 nuts. The spool holder should turn quite easily.

At last you need to put that whole thing onto the printer. The mounting holes should match the screws an the front right gantry near the SD card. You might change the screws to M3x8mm.

Usage

As you build it, the usage might be obvious now. Turn the holding arm by 90° to allow a spool to be placed onto the holder. The filament should start at the bottom. When the machine prints, the spool gets turned counter-clockwise.

I created this based on the spool holder of my other machine. I therefore remixed some of the parts as they are distributed freely.

I remixed the parts

  • LARGE_SPOOL_MOUNT.stl
  • SPOOL_MOUNT_BASE.stl
    from thing https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1450175/
Additional information

You might be interested in the pictures at
https://manuals.velleman.eu/article.php?id=7

description.text:

Make sure to test with both PLA and ABS at a variety of temperatures.  
The hotter the extrusion, the more liquid it is and more obvious the vibration artifacts will be. Also, PLA is much less viscous than ABS.  
Test with a variety of colors as well. Semi-transparent filaments tend to hide the vibration artifacts rather well. As do matte and very light filaments. Glossy black and opaque silver work very very well.  
Mind the X and Y orientation when slicing - having the labels correspond to actual X and Y axes will make debugging easier.

comments.text: There was no single thing. There are tons of little changes that contribute to reducing the vibration. For starters, knock off your acceleration and speed. Don't reduce the acceleration too much or you'll start getting blobbing, but anything above the values required to avoid that is unneccessary.

Recently started to play Star Wars Destiny - CCG/Dice Game, and rapidly realised I needed a better way to transport my dice and cards.

Version 2 Update:

The sides were taking forever to print on my machine and were trying to curl up at the corners, so I created Version 2 (HoloV2 Files).

The walls and top/bottom on the V2 are designed so that I can stick coloured/textured clear plastic from pocket files on to the back of the cube walls (better aesthetics).

I also tweaked the dice and card trays with some extra embossing and thinned the walls a bit to speed up printing.

The Version 2 Holocron is now 150mm on all sides.

Update:

Revised the dice tray to remove the bed mould lines. These were putting too much space between the dice and would have the dice rattling around. Also the removal of the mould lines increases capacity from 25 to 36 dice as the extra space allows an extra row and column of dice.

This is a support base for the kinect 360 to adapt it to any tripod mount. You will need to tap a thread into the center hole after printing, the best is to do this with a tap tool, if you don't have one you can do this by slowly and carefully screwing and unscrewing your tripod mount into the hole, make sure your screw is ALWAYS PERPENDICULAR to the hole and that you screw in a bit and then screw it out, then screw it in a bit more and screw it out again until there is a thread in the hole.

I've designed it to save material and printing time while maintaining structural integrity (that's why all the holes).

Should be printed with the flat part down in PLA at 100% infill to make sure the hooks are strong enough to click in and out without breaking.

title: [C-3PO] Costume from Don Post statue scans

description.text:
Hey guys !

This is the full C-3PO costume (without head and greeblies) from a Don Post statue.

My files are big, sorry for that but to work I needed maximum polygons.

Thank you Xeno to scanned that ! I worked hard to modified all that models, so please, don't make money with this stuff.

Xeno is okay to share all my work, because I'm not the scans owner, and I respect the Xeno's work.

I modified all the scans into a full wearable costume.

Be careful, you'll need some post prod !! Especially on the knees rings, the thighs, the back torso.

I'm not a 3D Modeller, I tried to do my best to modify this scans. If someone wants to modified my work and create a better version, don't hesitate !

If you have any questions, don't hesitate too.

Parts list :
ARMS.
TORSO.
LEFT LEG.
RIGHT LEG.
PANTS.
LEFT FOOT (I don't have the right foot ... Sorry !)

For some parts (shoulders ring and forearm), you can use the same for the both sides.

About the right thigh, you'll need some post prod with the plate. On the scans, the plate is not attached to the thigh. You have 2 versions, one with the plate (which requires some post prod but less) and one without the plate.

You will maybe have some scars on the back torso ... Sorry for that I don't have the skills to remove that.

I recommend to use big printer to print that parts.
I used Creality CR-10 to print all the costume. It took me 2-3 months to print all this costume.
To "glue" the differents parts (for example the differents torso pieces), I used PLA with my iron soldering and meld the two parts inside the costume. Outside, I used my iron soldering to meld the two parts without PLA, I just hide the line with the iron soldering. Be careful, and don't push too hard !).

To have the best adjustment with the thigh and the knee, I recommend to use heatgun (SLOWLY !!) and adapt the thigh on the knee.

To have a real beautiful chrome some options are available. I will use these steps to do mine :
Primer filler + sand (lot of sanding, sanding is life).
Black or White paint (glossy or not) 2K (paint with polyurethane resin).
Hydrochrome (you can find some videos on Youtube).
Varnish + gold tint SEM California gold 03126.

I recommend to add inside some fiberglass.

This spool holder shares all the features of TUSH that are important to me, it is simple to print and can be assembled without the needs of any tools or parts (like screws) except for the 608 bearings. It looks less fancy (curvy) than TUSH but it can easily be customized to fit any control box (or similar).

Background

I use TUSH and like it very much, but I needed some kind of brackets to safely put it on top of my Tevo Tornado control box. Since I wanted to check out OpenSCAD for some time I simply started to create a less fancy looking spool holder that shares the core features of TUSH.

Provided STLs

  • CUSH - Tevo Tornado Control Box.stl: With clamp for Tevo Tornado Control Box (tight fit)
  • CUSH - Tevo Tornado Control Box v1.1.stl: With clamp for Tevo Tornado Control Box (slightly wider fit, as suggested by godoloju)
  • CUSH - Tevo Tornado Control Box - Small Spool.stl: With clamp for Tevo Tornado Control Box in TUSH dimension (narrow) supporting smaller spools
  • CUSH - No Brackets.stl: Simply an example setup without clamps (TUSH dimensions)

Configuration

If you own the Tevo Tornado, or another printer with a controlbox that is exactly 15cm wide, you can download my Tevo Tornado STL file.

If you own a controlbox with different dimensions or if you have other requirements, check out the Customizer app.

Required Parts

  • 4x 608 ball bearings (for scooters, d=22mm, bore=8mm, t=7mm)

Print

As with TUSH, simply print the STL 4 times, add 4x 608 bearings and combine the parts. I printed the parts with PETG, 0,2mm layer height, 3 top/bottom layers, 3 shells and 35% infill (but 20% should be fine). I put some super glue on the bottom "separator" part, but it's completely optional.

Notes

Since the Customizer seems to be bugged atm, I can't really test it, so I hope it will be fixed soon.

The pictures are slightly different than the STLs. Why? First of all I printed my prototype and discovered that it fit perfectly, so I printed the other 3 parts using the same file. The prototype had these holes (just in case) but they are definitively not needed (I don't use them) so I removed them (can still be added via Customizer). Second of all I ever so slightly shortened the "clamp" brackets since they were unnecessarily long.

description.text:
This is a hollow cube with drain holes on the Z face and breather holes on the opposite face (build plate face) to minimise suction. Stick it on some supports to lift it off the build plate (Don't have it with the base on the build plate, that negates the breather holes and can ruin your FEP/PDMS), print it and measure. It has internal supports in the hollow space already, so none are required there.

When I used this on my Moai with v1.15 firmware, using "m" as the relevant cube measurement, the formula to calculate what entry to put in the relevant X or Y entry is:

900*(30/m)

I haven't used it on my D7 yest, but I'm sure you can work out what formula you would need to use.

description.text:
I was an idiot and ordered the wrong size of Noctua case fan. Then I was the same idiot and forced the included anti-vibration mounts through holes that were too small for them. A couple were beheaded and I was left with only two anti-vibration case fan mounts.

I modeled the mount using one of the remaining good ones as a reference.I highly recommend you use flex filament for this print. You know, so it will be flexy. I also recommend using one of the v2 files, it doesn't matter which (with or without a notch-- which I think was only present to make the solid rubber case fan mounts a little easier to pull through narrow holes). The v1 file might make sense if you are milling with a CNC, at which point I have to ask you how you think you're going to get a chunk of aluminum through a small hole. But that's your deal!

I printed mine in flex with 0% infill so it would just be made up of perimeters and be very squishy. This caused a problem with the base, which didn't print correctly since it was hollow. So I also created the modifier file and loaded it via Slic3r's modifier feature and set that portion to 100% infill.

Overall, my results were "okay," but I didn't end up using them because my case fan adapter made these kind of redundant. May my waste of time be a gift to you.

Mounting electronic components
The following steps seemed to be "optimal" and should be more-or-less self-explanatory - if not: take a look at the provided pictures)

  • Connect USB cable for power to Pi3 (tight fit in case, thus best done first)
  • Mount/screw Pi3 (back-side of top-half of casing, USB+LAN facing downwards)
  • Mount/screw speaker (bottom-side of bottom-half of casing)
  • Connect speaker JST-PH2.0 to re-speaker board
  • Connect GPIO-cable to re-speaker board
  • Mount/screw re-speaker board (back-side of bottom-half, connectors facing up)
  • If case printed in full:
    • Connect GPIO-cable to Pi3 (fold over for 90-degree angle)
    • Slide faceplace (without lens) into case
    • Insert lens into faceplate, for better fixation add some glue (probably a good idea to at first try assembling without glue)
  • If case printed in two parts:
    • Place lens in faceplate, for better fixation add some glue (probably a good idea to at first try assembling without glue)
    • Slide faceplace (with lens) into bottom-half
    • Connect GPIO-cable to Pi3 (fold over for 90-degree angle)
    • Slide case parts together

Software

  • Refer to mycroft / enclosure-picroft install instructions
  • Refer to respeaker install instructions

Electronics

  • LED indicator behind the camera lens (NeoPixel Jewel, 7x LED) for HAL-like effects

Software

  • LED indicator control (only when speaking...and/or listening after hotword detection?)
  • Snowboy or other hotword engine to act upon hard-coded commands (without mycroft parsing/handling)

In the Atari plug I used 3.96mm pitch contacts (for example). To wire the PCB you must first desolder the pin header and solder jumper to 5V on the bottom side of the PCB. Then connect:
SIO 3 (Data In) -> TXD (through Schottky diode Atari --|>I-- TXD)
SIO 4 (Ground) -> GND
SIO 5 (Data Out) -> RXD
SIO 7 (CMD) -> CTS
The diode can be omitted if you won't use the adapter in SIO daisy-chain.
You may want to use the transparent filament in order to see the RX/TX activity diodes on the PCB.

http://www.3ders.org/articles/20150405-maker-creates-modern-3d-printed-vertical-seder-plate-for-celebrating-passover.html

This is a 28mm scale (1/56th) model of the Soviet A-19 Model 1931 field gun gun. it is a rework of kpi1986's excellent file of the same gun.

The A-19 was the backbone of medium field artillery for the Red Army, and continued in use is different versions well into the Cold War. i did this up for use on the Bolt Action gaming table, where the gun is both a medium field gun as well as a heavy ATG.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/122_mm_gun_M1931_(A-19)

I took the original file, separated the gun barrel and breech area from the carriage. I created an axle and strengthened the vertical hydraulic recoil cylinders and the carriage itself; detailed the wheel hubs and tires, added a hand wheel on the right side of the gun (where an elevation wheel is located) and modified the spades on the end of the gun trails.

I printed this on a fine setting with rafts. As always, be careful removing the support material. you will find the wheels fit the hubs snuggly, so clean the wheel centre out. I glued the gun to the carriage with epoxy.

description.text:
I liked 2ROBOTGUY's combo lock a lot, but I wanted something that would work as a coin bank for my kids -- which my kids too young to understand ownership wouldn't be able to get into. I made a remix that was bigger and had a coin slot, but then I got thinking that it'd be nice to be able to change the combination.

Well, one thing led to another and so here is a fully customizeable version. The things that you can customize are:

  • Diameter
  • Height
  • Combination
    • Change the number of digits in the combo (this will affect minimum height)
    • Change the number of options, defaults to 10 but with larger diameter you could do many more
  • Thickness of the lock rings (the bits that stick out and make it a combination)
  • The height of the base
  • The font of the numbers on the base
  • The tolerance number (extra added to the radi

Again, this is mostly just 2ROBOTGUY's design, but I redesigned from the ground up in openscad and tweaked it a bit:

  • Added numbers at the bottom, which required shifting the notches slightly
  • Added a "ring" at the top to reduce the chance of "skipping" the top number (not yet shown in the pictures, I added it after the last prototype printed)
  • There are no symbols on the side of the outer cover

This part reinforces the rear of the Y carriage frame of the Anet A8. The other rear Y carriage frame reinforcements I have seen mount on the inside of the frame and are fairly large. This is a simpler reinforcement that mounts on the outside of the frame. The goal is to stiffen the rear frame to prevent it from flexing or cracking from Y belt tension. To install this frame remove the 2 mounting screws for the Y carriage stepper motor and replace them with 30mm screws. The holes are a bit tight so I recommend drilling them out with an 1/8 inch bit. There are also a few extra holes in the frame. I suggest you choose one (use a 15mm screw and nut) so that the frame is mounted on 3 points and does not move.

description.text:
This is a robust and surprisingly well working bearing. The design lets you make your own functional bearing despite the relative low accuracy of a 3D printer. If you get too much or too less play then change the tolerance for rolling surfaces and print the rollers again.

It is printed in parts so some easy assembly is necessary. All print-in-place bearings that I tried have too much play to be really useful. They just have to have a larger play else the parts would stick together when printing.

Please use the customizer to generate STL files for your specific need.

Credits go to TheGoofy and his Slew Bearing (see remix note). I just rebuilt it in OpenSCAD and designed the cage/spacer as one part.

Note that the bracket covers the USB port, this is simply because I had to put the support somewhere and the streamer can't be used if I blocked the power or HDMI connectors.

Also, you can't mirror this to connect the cables from the right because this would make the side "arm" cover one of the important ports (if you need to connect the cables from the right leave a comment and I'll see what I can do).

As always, if you find thsi useful I'll be gratful if you click "I made this" and upload a photo

description.text:
This holder for the Renkforce RF100 V2 is useful when the metal case of the extruder is removed, e.g. if you want to add an additional cooling fan. It serves two purposes, i.e., the filament is guided, similarly to the original metal tube (see also this thing), and it holds the cable to avoid strong bending and wear. No additional parts are needed, the original screws can be reused.

There are three versions of this thing:

Version A: Separated top and bottom part for easy printing, including support structures that can be rather easily removed. Simply slide the top part over the bottom part, it will snap in.

Version B: same as A but without support structures. Useful if you want to apply your own support.

Version C: monolithic, single piece. You need to figure out the best printing strategy yourself.

I only tested Version A. Please let me know if you face any problems.

There is an additional tube provided which can be glued to the top of versions A and B. It might be particularly useful when using flexible filaments as it holds the PTFE (Teflon) hose firmly.

Material: Any, including PLA (I tested PLA and PETG)

Renkforce RF100 V2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

100%

Notes:

Recommended printing settings (version A):

Bottom part:
Print slowly, the clip needs time to cool down. At least 15s per layer, better 20s or more. Or use active cooling by an additional Fan.
Layer height: 0.2mm
No support
Brim is recommended
Infill: 100%
Shell thickness: 1.2mm

Top part:
Same, but NO brim, otherwise the rubber hole support part may be hard to remove.
Can be printed faster.

Same as bottom part, but print even slower and with 30% infill to avoid warping. It worked well with 30s layer time and 1mm/s minimal speed. Actual print time was 50 minutes then.

description.text:
This is a very cheap rock tumbler.

You will need 4 skate board bearings, a motor, a power supply and some 1mm thick rubber sheet, all available off eBay.
Bearings I got here:
https://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/10pcs-Ball-Bearing-608ZZ-Bearing-Deep-Groove-Ball-Bearing-8mm-22mm-7mm-Useful/332464460888?ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT&_trksid=p2057872.m2749.l2649
£2.98 for 10, 29.8p each x 4 = £1.19
The rubber sheet I got here:
https://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/SOLID-RUBBER-SHEET-BLACK-1400MM-x-1MM-Leatherette-Commercial-Grade-Polymer/272537621896?ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT&_trksid=p2057872.m2749.l2649
I didn't use much, cost not worth mentioning.
The Motor I got here:
https://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/Miniature-motor-365-round-Motor-DC-12-24V-3000-RPM-6000-RPM-DC-Motor-DIY/401295531499?ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT&_trksid=p2057872.m2749.l2649
£2.27
The PSU was the most expensive, I bought this from Maplin, set to 12V:
https://www.maplin.co.uk/p/6w-multi-voltage-acdc-power-supply-xx09k
£9.99
So, less than £15 all together for a finished rock roller.

I took off the PSU connector and soldered the wires directly to the motor, turn on and off using mains switch on wall socket.
It runs at about 1 revolution per second.

Rubber sheet is used inside end caps of drum to seal (make it water tight), used inside and outside drum (to quieten), used on rollers and outside of lids (grip).
The drive band is created by mixing up oogoo, putting into mould and letting set.
Each band appears to last about a month, been trying to create drive bands from rubber sheet, but not been successful yet.
I've also created a plywood box which is carpeted inside and out with carpet tiles to further quieten it, but I'm not totally convinced this works.

I've had 2 of these running for 24 hours per day, 1 week for each stage.
For details and pictures details of rock rolling still in progress, see here:
http://trevmhomers.blogspot.co.uk/2017/12/rock-tumbler.html
I still have not completed a full set of stones polishing through 4 stages to nice and shiny.

title: Hook for mini gantry for 20x20 aluminum extrusion x-axis conversion

description.text:
There is a great x-axis conversion for 20x20 aluminum extrusion
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1285301

I did a remix for it for my tronxy p802ma printer
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2766399

However, the conversion requires using 20 tooth pulley and idler, otherwise the belt is not parallel to the axis.

To understand: with 16 tooth pulley/idler the problem is not visible in the center of a bed because error is only 0.006mm. However, close to the edge the error becomes as large as 0.5mm.

I did not want to use 20 tooth pulley/idler because resolution is decreased by 25% and torque also decreases by 25-28%.

So, i created a special hook which pushes the belt into the extrusion, so the belt goes parallel to the axis.

I am testing now. First test prints turned out great. Well, not worse than in the center of the bed. The whole x-axis conversion just makes everything better.

I provided two versions. The flange is very thin (only 2.4mm) and can break off easily. When i printed mine one broke when i tried to insert it. I simply melted a screw into it.
So, i did a second version with two 1mm holes where you can put little metal pieces. Better melt them into the holes.

Installation is hell. You will either need a lot longer piece of belt or tied a thread to one end to pull it through the holding hole later.

The procedure:
1) Secure one end of a belt into one hook
2) Insert hook into mini gantry
3) Trace the belt into the extrusion, through the left z holder, motor holder, turn around, through the right z holder, through the idler, again right z holder (return path)
4) pull into the right hook belt hole
5) insert hook into the gantry
6) put the gantry on the extrusion
7) secure the belt on the right hook
8) tension the belt

Securing the belt is simple - fold the end of belt and push it back into the hole, insert a pint into the belt loop, as small as 0.5mm in diameter.

Printing:
PLA, turn it 180 around, supports needed, 0.2mm per layer, 100% infill
Lots of work to remove the supports and the sand everything so it goes smoothly into the extrusion.

I provided solidworks files, fill free to play with the design.

Final thoughts:

Originally i did a hook like this for Y axis conversion (not published and not finished yet). There it seems as the only way to go. However, for X axis now i thing is not really necessary. A better way would be to go with 20 teeth pulley/idler and just secure the belt from the inner side, so it is as parallel as possible. The error will be negligible this way.
The resolution will drop from 0.01mm to 0.0125mm, but it is totally beyond error which is introduced even by the extrusion process itself. However torque will be decreased by as much as 30%, but we are on wheels now, and do not need as much torque. Maybe only for stopping after acceleration, but anyway nobody notices any problems.

However, for Y axis 16 teeth, i think, are necessary, because the weight is a lot more and we need as much torque as we can get.

UPDATE 06/02/2018:
Printed 0.5kg of plastic with it- not problem.

title: Customizable FilamentGuide for MK8 Extruder Drives
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a customizable filament guide for MK8 extruder with 1.75mm filament. Usually, such a guide is need if you want to print softer or flexible filaments. Or if you want a smooth filament transportation system from the spool to the print head.

There are some filament guides for MK8 extruders out there, like

  • https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2129179
  • https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1450174
  • https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1540487
  • https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1257448
  • https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2502215 ... they all gave me somehow inspiration (so thank you guys for sharing your good work!)

However, they all did not combine all of the following properties:

  • guide the filament as early as possible
  • guide the outgoing bowden tube, which smoothly fits in the filament guide, so that we can use a push through bowden connector (see attached images)
  • fixed to the frame so that we can retract the filament without retracting the bowden tube through the push through connector (yes, this can happen)
  • beeing customizable and with free to use openscad file

So this is how this thing comes into play. You have the following options, either just use my pre-generated stl files for left and right type MK8 standard extruders, or customize it!

  • Start the customizer
  • Adapt the required values, like spacing values bowden tube diameter, or filament guide gear
  • Select the type (right hand or left hand type) and ...
  • Generate your customized guide
  • Print and Enjoy!

Have also a look at my other customizable things or projects.

The highest magnifications can be achieved by inverting (putting upside down) the webcam lens (no extra lens needed!). Addition of good lighting by the use of leds allows to see single cells such as blood or yeast cells. See here how to do the hack:

The design is for a laser cut inverted microscope stage. The design is fully customizable including the thickness of the materials used. To adapt to your webcam an adjustement of the object plate position is built into the design. Focus can be set via the focus wheel. Customizer is not yet able to create 2D drawings. If you want to export the design as .dxf, you should download the .scad file, and open it on you computer with OpenScad. Then you can edit manualy the size of the microscope, change the ouput type to DXF and export your creation. And here for more stage types:

description.text:
This Gloomhaven storage solution uses Harbor Freight "20 Bin Portable Parts Storage Case" https://www.harborfreight.com/19-bin-portable-parts-storage-case-93928.html - item 93928.

Print List
1 Store Divider Stand
3 Store Dividers
6 Monster Standee Trays
1 Boss Standee Tray
1 Monster Stats Tray
2 Event Boxes
4 Event Box Dividers

The "Store" fits in a single large 2x2 tray. Print 3 dividers, as you have four stacks: your current store, your prosperity-gained store cards, designs from chests, and your random items. (A future design may build the side-panel directly into a box, instead of just resting on its side.)

The "Monster Standee Tray" replaces a large tray+two smalls (basically 6 smalls, 3 across by 2 down). You should be able to stack them 3 high. There is enough room for 6 standees per spot, with 6 spots on each tray.

The "Boss Standee Tray" is a similar tray to the Monster Standee Tray (3x2) - it has one extra large spot for the stone golems, and the rest of the space is open for the larger boss standees.

The "Monster Stats Tray" replaces a large tray+two smalls (3x2). The hole in the bottom of the box is to let you push the cards through from the back, for ease of use. There is enough room to stack one of the Monster Standee trays on top.

The "Event Box" replaces a single large 2x2 tray. The hole in the bottom of the box is to let you push cards through from the back, for ease of use. The locked cards go in the bottom, with a separator above it. Cards that were experienced but not trashed, go above that. Another separator goes above those cards, until you shuffle the experienced cards back in. (This occurs when you add a card to that event deck.) Unlocked and non-shuffled cards go on the top layer.

Update: Added "Dead Card Box" for event & random side locations that are removed from game.

Update 3/2/2018: Added "Store_Box_Alternative_to_Stand", where you can print a box with the window built-in...instead of using the Stand inside a default yellow Harbor Freight box. If you print this, you do not need "Store_Divider_Stand".

title: Tonearm Lock for (some) Technics SL Model Turntables

description.text:
One of the most annoying things that I find when I buy a used, beat-up turntable, is that the tonearm lock is broken off. This will let you replace your tonearm lock on some Technics SL model turntables. I made this one specifically for a Technics SL-5200. I held it close to my SL-D2, and it looks like it would fit. I looked up other SL model turntables, and it looks like it should fit some of those as well, but I can't be 100% sure about that.
With some slight modifications, it could fit other turntables, too. Feel free to edit the Sketchup files to fit your turntable.

There are two versions of the lock included. One of them, named TTL, has supports and is more printer-friendly. You'll have to sand it down slightly before it'll fit in the hole. The second file, named TTL V2, doesn't have the small support structure, and should fit without any sanding. I couldn't test this because my printer is lower-end. In theory, it should work.
